Here's how to implement all three requirements:

## 1. Custom "Cancel" back button on `EditProductPage`

```xml
<!-- EditProductPage.xaml -->
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- your form content -->
</ContentPage>
```

## 2. ViewModel with confirmation logic

```csharp
// EditProductViewModel.cs
public partial class EditProductViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    public ICommand BackCommand { get; }

    public EditProductViewModel()
    {
        BackCommand = new AsyncRelayCommand(OnBackAsync);
    }

    private async Task OnBackAsync()
    {
        if (HasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage
                .DisplayAlert("Unsaved Changes",
                              "Discard your changes?",
                              "Discard", "Stay");
            if (!discard)
                return; // cancel navigation
        }

        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

## 3. Guard the system back gesture/button in `AppShell`

The custom `BackCommand` handles the in-page button, but the user can also swipe back or press the hardware back button. Guard that in `AppShell.xaml.cs`:

```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.BindingContext is EditProductViewModel vm
        && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await page.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "Discard your changes?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `BackButtonBehavior` with `TextOverride="Cancel"` replaces the default back arrow with a "Cancel" label.
- Its `Command` binding handles taps on that button — bypassing the default pop, so you control navigation.
- `OnNavigating` with `GetDeferral()` catches system-level back gestures (swipe, hardware button) that bypass your custom command. Always call `deferral.Complete()` whether you cancel or not.
